      • deleteItem

        public boolean deleteItem(int... optionalIndex)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Removes a single item from the array of items stored at the current cursor position. If only one item is stored at the current position, then the entire current entry is deleted (both tag and object). If only one item is present, the index must be zero, or omitted. This is true whether the current item is a single item or an array containing one item. If an index is specified, it must be less than the number of repeating values present (zero is the index of the first item). An index of -1 is interpreted as the index of the last item (i.e. count() - 1). It is an error if the cursor is unpositioned, or the index is outside of the range of items, of if repeating values are present and an index is not specified. If one or more items remain after the specified item is deleted, false is returned and the cursor remains unpositioned. If the last or only remaining item at the current position is deleted, the entire entry (tag and object) is deleted. When this happens, the cursor is positioned on the next tag, and true is returned. If there is no next tag, the cursor is positioned on the previous tag and false is returned. If there are no reaming tags, the cursor is unpositioned. In other words, true is only returned when the cursor is moved forward to the next tag because all items have been removed from the current item array. This behavior is similar to legacy IDataCursor delete() behavior.
        Specified by:
        deleteItem in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        optionalIndex - optional offset (starting at zero) into the array if repeating values present
        Returns:
        true if cursor is positioned on the next item after deletion

      • deleteObject

        public boolean deleteObject()
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Removes the tag-object-pair (single value or array of repeating values) from the current position. If there are tags following the current position, the cursor is positioned on the next tag and true is returned. If there is no next tag, the cursor is positioned on the previous tag and false is returned. If there are no remaining tags, the cursor is unpositioned and false is returned. This behavior is similar to legacy IDataCursor delete() behavior.
        Specified by:
        deleteObject in interface XmlDataCursor
        Returns:
        true if cursor is positioned on the next item after deletion

      • getItem

        public java.lang.Object getItem(int... optionalIndex)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Returns an item from the current-object. If repeating values are present, an index must be specified. If the current-tag is an element-tag, a value is returned. If the current-tag is a group-tag, a group-value is returned. If the current-tag is an indirect-tag, an indirect-item iis returned (either an any-item or substitution-item). It is an error if the cursor is not positioned. It is an error if an array with more than one value is present and no index is specified. If a scalar is present, the index may be specified as zero or omitted. If an index is specified, the item at that offset in the array is returned. It is an error if index exceeds the number of items present. An index of -1 is equal to the index of the last repeating value. If the current-object is a scalar and an index of 0 or -1 is specified, the value is returned; otherwise it is an error to specify an index for a scalar value. Empty values are always be represented as empty Strings or empty IDatas, never as Java nulls.
        Specified by:
        getItem in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        optionalIndex - offset into the repeating values array (if repeating values are present)
        Returns:
        the requested value

      • getAnyTag

        public XmlDataContentTag getAnyTag(int... optionalIndex)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Returns the item tag present in the *any Document. The returned tag will be an instance of XmlDataElementTag or XmlDataSubstitutionTag. This is a very specialized method. More typically, getValueTag() is used to return the tag associated with the item. However, if the *any document references a substitution group, the getValueTag() method returns the element tag present in the substitution group. This specialized method returns the tag stored in the *any document which will be either be a element tag or a substitution tag. This method is used only when it is necessary to distinguish between substitution tags and element tags in a *any document. Normally, getTagValue() will be sufficient, and more general.
        Specified by:
        getAnyTag in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        optionalIndex - offset into the repeating item array (if repeating values are present)
        Returns:
        The tag present in the *any Document.

      • insertItemAfter

        public void insertItemAfter(java.lang.Object value,
                            int index)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Inserts a repeating value after the specified index into the array of repeating values at the current-position (the current-object). Insert an item into an array of repeating values at the current tag, after the specified index. An index of -1 causes the item to be appended to the end of the array. Otherwise, the index must be a number between 0 and the length of the array minus 1. When the current-tag is a substitution-tag, the value must be a substitution-item. When the current-tag is an any-tag, the value must be an an any-item. These item may be created, for example, using XmlData.createSubstitutionItem(XmlDataElementTag, Object) or XmlData.createAnyItem(XmlDataContentTag, Object). If the current-object is a scalar, it is promoted to an array prior to insertion of the new item. If the cursor has recast set to true, the new array is an Object[].
        Specified by:
        insertItemAfter in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        value - the scalar value inserted (must be simple-value, group-value, complex-value, or indirect-item)
        index - The insert position after which the value is inserted)

      • insertValueAfter

        public void insertValueAfter(XmlDataContentTag tag,
                             java.lang.Object value,
                             int index)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Insert a value into an array of repeating values at the current-position, after the specified index. An index of -1 causes the item to be appended to the end of the array. Otherwise, the index must be a number between 0 and the length of the array minus 1. If the current-tag is an element-tag or group-tag, the value is inserted directly into the repeating value array at the specified offset. The content-tag is irrelevant (for groups and elements) and may be null. If not null, it must match the current tag. If the current-tag is a substitution-tag or an any-tag, a substitution-item or any-item is created from the content-tag and value, and inserted into the repeating values at the specified index offset. If the current Object is a scalar it is promoted to an array prior to insertion of the new item. If the cursor has recast set to true, the new array is an Object[].
        Specified by:

        tag - the name of the repeating value for indirect-items (may be null if current tag is an element and group)
        value - the value to insert (if the current tag is an any tag and the content tag is a substitution tag, value must be a substitution value).
        index - the index of the repeating item

      • setItem

        public void setItem(java.lang.Object value,
                    int... optionalIndex)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Stores a value or an indirect-item at the current cursor position. If the current cursor is positioned on a repeating value, an index must be specified. It is an error if the cursor is unpositioned. The value stored must be a simple-value, a group-value, a complex-value, or an indirect-item. Empty values should be represented by empty Strings or empty IData. For Document Type directed conversion, a repeating value is always represented as either a String[] or an IData[], or Object[]s, as appropriate. For non-directed conversion, repeating values are always stored as Object[]s.

        It is always preferable to use one of the XmlData methods to construct the value if it is not a String or String[]. For example, use XmlData.createGroupValue(Object...) if the content does not contain attributes and the top-level group does not contain repeating values. Otherwise use XmlData.createComplexValue(). When creating an indirect-item, use a methods such as XmlData.createAnyItem(XmlDataContentTag, Object) to create an any-item or a method such as XmlData.createSubstitutionItem(XmlDataElementTag, Object) to create a substitution-item.

        If an index is specified, the specified value in the array of repeating values is set and any associated attributes cleared. When no index is specified, the object must be scalar String or IData object. An index of -1 is equivalent to the index of the last repeating item. It is an error if the value is incompatible with the current tag. For example, *substitution, *group, and *any tags only accept an IData as value. If tag and content are not compatible, the TagAndContentConflict exception is thrown.

        Specified by:
        setItem in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        value - the value to be replaced.
        optionalIndex - the position in the list of repeating values to be set. When index is specified, the value may not be an array.

      • setValue

        public void setValue(java.lang.Object value,
                     int... optionalIndex)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Sets the value at the current cursor position (and index if repeating values are present). For element and group tags, the value (simple, group, or complex) is stored directly at the current position (and index). For any and substitution tags, the value tag is stored in the indirect-item value. (substitution-item or any-item). For XmlDataElementTags, the item must be a String or IData object. For XmlDataGroupTags, it must be an IData. If there is an existing object and it is an array, an index must be specified. For an XmlDataAnyTag, the object is stored indirectly; it is stored in the *content field of the *any Document object. For an XmlDataSubstitutionTag, the item is stored indirectly; it is stored as the object of a single child which contains group content representing the substituted tag/object.
        Specified by:
        setValue in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        value - the IData or String object that ia assigned as the value of the current cursor position.
        optionalIndex - the offset into the repeating values if the current item is an array.

      • setValueTag

        public void setValueTag(XmlDataContentTag key,
                        int... index)
        Description copied from interface: XmlDataCursor
        Sets the tag of the value stored at the current cursor. If the current tag is an element or a group tag, the new tag is stored directly in the tag/value pair. In this case, setValueTag() behaves exactly like XmlDataCursor.setTag(XmlDataContentTag). However, if the current value is an indirect-item, the tag is stored in the indirect-item. If the indirect-item is an any-item, the tag is decomposed and stored in the *ncName and *namespace fields of the any-item. The current tag remains unchanged. If the current tag is a substitution-tag, the value tag is stored as the tag of the first and only child in the substitution-item. The index parameter only has meaning for substitution and any objects (names of repeated elements and groups are identical for all entries).
        Specified by:
        setValueTag in interface XmlDataCursor
        Parameters:
        key - the tag assigned to the current value
        index - the offset into the repeating value array.
